<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>WWC0031</title></head><body><div><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:right;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">1</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">WWC0031</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Professor Robert Plomin</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Institute of Psychiatry, King’s College London</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Education has not yet come to grips with evidence about the nature (genetics) and nurture (environment) of individual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">differences in children’s academic achievement and underachievement. Differences between children are often assumed to be entirely caused by variation in family, school, teacher and peer environments – but research by me, and many others in several countri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es, shows that genetic (DNA) differences between children account for more than half of the differences between children in their educational achievement. By contrast, only about a fifth of the differences between children in educational achievement is acc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ounted for by schools. No specific policy implications follow directly from recognising genetic differences between children in how easily -- they learn even basic literacy and numeracy skills. Nonetheless, it cannot be right to ignore genetics in discussi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ons about why children differ in their educational achievement.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I was asked to provide no more than two pages of written evidence. In what follows, I cite my own research as evidence, although the papers cited also summarise other research. General backgr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ound information can be found in the sixth edition of the major textbook in the field </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Plomin, DeFries, Knopik, &amp; Neiderhiser, 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and specific background reading about genetics and education can be found in a book that has just been published on the top</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Asbury &amp; Plomin, 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">More than half of the differences </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> children in their educational achievement is caused by genetic (DNA) differences </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> them. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These genetic differences are just as strong in the early schools years, when for exampl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e children are learning to read </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Kovas, Haworth, Dale, &amp; Plomin, 2007)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as they are in the later school years when children are reading to learn </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Kovas et al., 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Our most recent research on GCSE scores shows similarly substantial genetic influence at a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ge 16 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Shakeshaft et al., in press)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Finding that genetic differences account for more than half of the differences between children in their reading achievement (that reading is heritable) does </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> mean that half of a particular child’s ability to read is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> due to their genes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Asbury &amp; Plomin, 2013; Haworth &amp; Plomin, 2011)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This is because heritability is a population-level measure, it tells us something about people not a particular person. It is nonetheless useful in the same way that other population-leve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l estimates have been (such as the population-level research that revealed harm caused by smoking). Our research concerns children in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, given the genetic and environmental differences that exist here now.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The genetic factors that contribute to unde</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rachievement also influence individual differences throughout the entire distribution of educational achievement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">That is, when genes are identified that are responsible for genetic influence on reading disability, the same genes will be responsible for in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dividual differences in reading ability throughout the distribution, from poor readers to average readers to excellent readers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Plomin, Shakeshaft, McMillan, &amp; Trzaskowski, 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Throughout the life sciences, common disorders are generally the quantitativ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e extreme of the same genetic factors responsible for normal variation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Plomin, Haworth, &amp; Davis, 2009)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Genetic influence is just as strong for all aspects of the National Curriculum, for example, for literacy as much as for numeracy. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Another example is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Phonics Screening Check administered to Key Stage 1 pupils: We show substantial genetic influence for this phonics test at age 7 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Harlaar, Spinath, Dale, &amp; Plomin, 2005)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and age 12 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Harlaar, Dale, &amp; Plomin, 2007)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. For GCSE scores, genetic influence is just as high for the three compulsory courses of English, Mathematics and Science </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Shakeshaft et al., in press)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Value-added measures of educational achievement show just as much genetic influence as uncorrected mea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sures. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although it has been assumed that value-added measures – such as correcting for previous achievement, family background or intelligence – are pure measures of environmental influence, such value-added measures in fact show as much genetic influence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as uncorrected measures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Haworth, Asbury, Dale, &amp; Plomin, 2011)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Genetic factors do not differ in quality or quantity for boys and girls.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We find that average achievement differences between boys and girls are small relative to individual differences. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndependent of the existence of average differences in achievement, comparing genetic results for same-sex and opposite-sex twin pairs suggests that there are no important qualitative or quantitative genetic differences as they affect the educational achiev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ement of boys and girls.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">New research techniques using DNA alone confirm the importance of genetics for educational achievement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most research has been based on the classical twin method that compares monozygotic (identical) twins to dizygotic (non-identi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cal) twins; our results are based on our Twins Early Development Study (TEDS), which consists of all twins born in England and Wales </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1994-96 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Haworth, Davis, &amp; Plomin, 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The results from twin studies are being confirmed by new research based d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">irectly on DNA differences between unrelated individuals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Harlaar, Trzaskowski, Dale, &amp; Plomin, in press; Plomin, DeFries, et al., 2013; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Trzaskowski</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> et al.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Nonetheless, despite the rapid advances in molecular genetics, it continues to be difficult </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to identify the specific genes responsible for genetic influence on educational achievement, just as is the case for all complex traits and common disorders throughout the life sciences </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Plomin &amp; Simpson, in press)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.   </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recognising the extent of genetic in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">fluence on individual differences in educational achievement is consistent with personalised learning. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Genetic evidence speaks very clearly – there are large differences in likely academic ability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> people which may not be easily reduced. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rather than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a one-size-fits-all approach to education, recognising and respecting genetically driven individual differences in children’s appetites as well as aptitudes suggests the need for an individually tailored approach in education, to maximize children’s stren</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gths and minimize their weaknesses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Asbury &amp; Plomin, 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Reference List</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Asbury, K., &amp; Plomin, R. (2013). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">G is for genes: What genetics can teach us about how we teach our children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Oxford: Wiley Blackwell.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Harlaar, N., Dale, P. S., &amp;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Plomin, R. (2007). Reading exposure: A (largely) environmental risk factor with environmentally-mediated effects on reading performance in the primary school years. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Journal of Child Psychology and Psychiatry, 48</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, 1192-1199. </span><br /><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1469-7610.2007.01798.x"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">doi: 1</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">0.1111/j.1469-7610.2007.01798.x</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt